                				        <div id="content">
                    <div id="content-content" class="clear-block"> <script type="text/javascript">var re="";</script>
<div class="artwork-content">
    <div id="artwork-details">
        <div id="tombstone">
   
    <p><strong>07. "Pittsburgh Color Dynamics." Pittsburgh Plate Glass Company; c.1950s.</strong><br />       <p>According to the recommendations of color theorist Faber Birren in a 1968 essay on color and worker productivity, &ldquo;It is fallacious to assume that because color is appealing and attractive, it is conducive to enjoyable labor. Indeed, for the very reason of its strong impact, it may, when not properly applied, distract from work, interfere with tasks, and actually make seeing difficult and fatiguing.&rdquo;<sup><a href="3541#fn36" id="ref36">36</a></sup>  Just as dangerous, however, was an office devoid of color, which &ldquo;might well impair human efficiency and break down morale by causing irrelevant daydreams.&rdquo;<sup><a href="3541#fn37" id="ref37">37</a></sup></p>
<p>Though color theory has existed for millennia, &ldquo;color psychology&rdquo; has only come to the fore over the last century, largely through the work of Birren, Carolyn Bloomer, and Max Lüscher. Seeking inexpensive methods of improving efficiency and productivity in the workplace, corporations sought the advice of such experts to help improve office design while manufacturers, seeking income, coopted this new science for their own benefit (note the paint color &ldquo;eye rest green&rdquo; in the upper left panel of this spread).</p>
<p>Though bright colors had become favored again in the home during the 1930s, office designers remained color-averse until the mid 1950s when the &ldquo;business-like look [gave] way to colorful interiors with almost a home-like atmosphere.&rdquo;<sup><a href="3541#fn38" id="ref38">38</a></sup></p>
<br />
<p></p>
 <p><sup id="fn36">36. Faber Birren, &ldquo;Impact of Color on Employee Morale and Productivity,&rdquo; <em>New Concepts in Office Design</em>, (Elmhurst, Ill. : Business Press, 1968), 86. <a href="3541#ref36" title="Jump back to footnote 36 in the text.">↩</a></p><p><sup id="fn37">37. Ibid, 87.<a href="3541#ref37" title="Jump back to footnote 37 in the text.">↩</a></p><p><sup id="fn38">38. Sara O. Marberry, <em>Color in the Office: Design Trends from 1950-1990 and Beyond</em><strong>, </strong>(New York: Van Nostrand Reinhold, [1994]), 16.<a href="3541#ref38" title="Jump back to footnote 38 in the text.">↩</a></p><br /><br />
    	 "Tools of the Trade: 19th- and 20th-Century Architectural Trade Catalogs," Case 6, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, August 4, 2015-October 12, 2015.<br />
<br />
<a href="http://digital-libraries.saic.edu/cdm/ref/collection/mqc/id/68807">Link to R&amp;B Archives Digital Collections record</a><br />    	    </p>

    </div><!--/tombstone-->
